2.1 Markovian Decision Processes
The control problems considered in this paper can be described as Markovian De-
cision Processes (MDPs). An MDP is described by a set Sof states, a set Aof ac-
tions, a stochastic transition function p(s, a, s/prime) describing the (stochastic) system
behavior and an immediate reward or cost function c:S×A→R. The goal is to
ﬁnd an optimal policy π∗:S→A, that minimizes the expected cumulated costs
for each state. In particular, we allow Sto be continuous, assume Ato be ﬁnite
for our learning system, and pto be unknown to our learning system (model-free
approach). Decisions are taken in regular time steps with a constant cycle time.
