Time-Weighted Cumulative LSTM Method Using Log Data
for Predicting Credit Card Customer Turnover
JINYONG EOM
1AND JAEKWANG KIM
1,2, (Member, IEEE)
1Department of Applied Data Science, Sungkyunkwan University, Seoul 03063, Republic of Korea
2School of Convergence/Convergence Program for Social Innovation, Sungkyunkwan University, Seoul 03063, Republic of Korea
Corresponding author: Jaekwang Kim (linux@skku.edu)
This work was supported by the Ministry of Science and ICT (MSIT), South Korea, through the ICT Creative Consilience Program
supervised by the Institute for Information and Communications Technology Planning and Evaluation (IITP) under Grant
IITP-2023-2020-0-01821.
ABSTRACT One of the most important challenges for credit card companies is to retain customers.
To achieve this, they predict whether customers will use credit cards and respond preemptively through
marketing. Improper prediction leads to an increase in marketing costs; therefore, improving the performance
of the prediction model is an important challenge for credit card companies. Therefore, credit card companies
are working toward increasing the predictive power of the model, but the data used for learning are limited to
formal data, such as card payment data; the log history stored on the application is not used. Prediction models
using sequence data, such as log history, are being studied. However, no studies so far have appropriately
utilized card payment data, log history, and information on the timing of the elements constituting the
sequence. In this paper, we propose a method for predicting credit card turnover using application log and
credit card payment data. The method embeds log data and weights each log using a term-weighting function.
In addition, the time difference between the day customers visit the app and the last day of the month in which
they leave is calculated. The weight value is higher when the timespan is shorter. The weighted log data were
trained with a 2-layer LSTM model and its output layer was combined with the output layer trained with the
card payment data for customer turnover prediction. It was verified that the model presented in this paper had
a higher performance than the model using only card payment data and the model using only a time-weighted
log sequence.
INDEX TERMS Term-weighting, time weighted model, log analysis, predictive models.
I. INTRODUCTION
Most Koreans use credit cards as a payment method.
Therefore, if a card company’s customer has not used a
credit card for a month, it usually means that they have used
another card company’s credit card. Credit card companies
define this as customer departure and try to prevent it through
marketing. However, in the marketing process, customers
who would not have departed are also targeted, resulting in
increasing marketing costs, and decreasing efficiency. This is
an important challenge for credit card companies.
The models originally used by credit card companies were
mainly trained with formal data, such as card payment data.
Unstructured data, such as log history on card company
The associate editor coordinating the review of this manuscript and
approving it for publication was Dost Muhammad Khan
 .applications, were not used for analysis. In addition, studies
on financial data-based models such as credit card fraud
detection and credit card default prediction mainly used
structured data such as usage amount [1], [2].
However, the log data contains important information that
can predict the customer’s future usage pattern, which means
not using it is like missing important variables in customer
turnover. The app log data is now one of the important
information for predicting customers’ usage patterns because
behavior such as issuing new cards is possible through the
app, and the number of customers using the app is continually
increasing.
Attempts have been made to reflect the characteristics
of the components of a sequence in a sequence data-based
predictive model study, such as log data [3], [4], [5]. This has
a limitation of missing information regarding the occurrence
VOLUME 11, 2023This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives 4.0 License.
For more information, see https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ 18245J. Eom, J. Kim: Time-Weighted Cumulative LSTM Method Using Log Data for Predicting Credit Card Customer Turnover
of the sequence. In contrast, several attempts have been
made to reflect information regarding the time at which the
sequence occurs [6]. However, it also has a limitation in that it
does not reflect the characteristics of sequence components.
To make the most of the information in log history
data, both the characteristics of each log page and the
information when each customer accessed the application
must be utilized. For example, if turnover customers visit
more pages than loyal customers, it is likely to be meaningful
information for turnover prediction. Therefore, we designed a
weight function, mainly used in natural language processing,
to utilize the frequency of customer visits and log history
pattern information of customers and turnover customers.
Additionally, log histories that were accessed most recently
are likely to provide more meaningful information for
turnover prediction than log histories that were previously
accessed. Therefore, if a customer has recently accessed a
card company’s app, the information should receive a higher
weight.
In this study, we propose a prediction model based on
LSTM; the model applies time weights and term weights
to credit card application logs and combines them with the
output of the model trained with card payment data to predict
customer turnover. The validity of the model was verified by
comparing the card payment data-based model used by credit
card companies, the model applying only the term weight,
and the model applying only the time weight.
II. RELATED WORK
A. PREDICTION USING THE WEIGHT OF SEQUENCE DATA
To make the most of the information in sequence data, studies
have been conducted using data that have been weighted in
various ways.
First, studies that reflected the time at which the sequence
occurred were conducted. In a paper published in 2017, Zhao
et al. [6] tried to predict the following week’s stock price trend
by reflecting the time weight of the past stock price trend.
Each stock price was classified into three types of sequences:
1) upward trend, 2) downward trend, and 3) no trend. The time
difference to the next time point was calculated, and the closer
the time point, the higher the weight added to the learning.
This method is limited in that it considers each element to
have the same characteristics, but the elements constituting
the sequence have distinct characteristics.
Studies have also been conducted to reflect the frequency
of occurrence of each element constituting a sequence
[7], [8], [9]. This is typically used in natural language
processing. Yuan et al [7] suggested giving term frequency-
inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) weights based on the
frequency of occurrence of words to textual emotion analysis
and tried to learn by reflecting the importance of each
word in the text. To classify whether sentences on simple
notation services (SNS) are sarcasm identified, Onan [8]
tested various weight functions to reflect the importance
of each word in learning. Their research results of the
model that used a supervised weighting function, show better
predictive performance than the existing model that uses
TD-IDF, which is an unsupervised weighting function. Thesubsequent studies learned in such a way that sequences
occurred simultaneously, without considering the time when
each sequence occurred. This was a limitation because it
could not reflect the time information contained in each
sequence.
B. PREDICTION USING LOG DATA
Research using log data has mainly been conducted in
relation to anomaly detection. In Christophe Bertero’s
paper [3], each online log was recognized as a word to apply
to natural language processing learning. They first parsed
the logs, then vectorized and learned through embedding,
showing an improvement in the performance of the anomaly
detection model. Similarly, Wang et al. [4] studied how
to parse and embed logs and then applied various weight
functions according to the frequency of occurrence of each
log. The weight function was applied to the logs to reflect the
importance of each log. Using the weighted data for learning
produced better results in anomaly detection. The method
used in the previous study did not reflect the time at which
each log occurred, as mentioned above.
C. TERM WEIGHT FUNCTION
When classifying the types or properties of documents, each
term constituting the document has a unique importance. It is
difficult to say whether a particular word that occurs fre-
quently simply represents the characteristics of the document.
Likewise, a rare occurrence does not mean that the word is
not important for understanding the document. To address
this problem, especially when classifying documents, a term-
weighting study was conducted to reflect the importance
of each term. This section describes the term weights TF-
IDF, term frequency-relevance frequency (TF-RF), term
frequency-inverse gravity moment (TF-IGM), and term
frequency-inverted category frequency (TF-ICM) used in this
study.
1) TF-IDF
TF-IDF is based on the proposition that the importance of
a particular term is proportional to the number of times the
term appears and inversely proportional to the total number
of documents that the term is mentioned [10]. The TF-IDF
weights are expressed as follows:
