Vol.32, No.1, Jan. 2023resulting in poor generalization performance. Therefore,
learning from noisy labels has become a potential and
important problem in the automatic tongue diagnosis of
TCM.
In 2015, Hinton et al. [1 ] proposed the concept of
“distillation,” which  transfer  the  knowledge  learned
from a cumbersome deep network (teacher network) in-
to a small and simple network (student network). Spe-
cifically, the prediction probability of the teacher mod-
el is used as a “soft target” to assist the training and
learning of the student model. Inspired by this, in this
paper, we  propose  a  confident-learning-assisted  know-
ledge distillation (CLA-KD) framework for tongue col-
or classification  with  noisy  labels.  We  design  an  en-
semble teacher network, named E-CA2-ResNet18 in our
scenario. Its another important role is to perform con-
fident learning (CL), identifying, correcting and cleans-
ing  noisy  labels.  Thus,  the  knowledge  can  be  learned
from the corrected labels and clean labels, which will be
then transferred to the student network. Concretely, we
distill the knowledge learned the entire noisy dataset to
hunt more clean samples and then to enhance the final
model. Through integrating CL into the general distilla-
tion  framework,  the  joint  probability  distribution
among soft labels and hard labels can be explicitly ap-
plied in the learning process of student network, which
facilitates to disambiguate the noisy labels.
In summary, we make the following contributions:
1)  We  propose  a  novel  framework,  named  CLA-
KD, for tongue color classification with noisy labels. CL
is  incorporated  into  the  knowledge  distillation  (KD)
framework  to  identify  and  cleanse  noisy  labels,  which
enables the  knowledge  transferred  to  the  student  net-
work learned from the corrected labels. And thus, the
influence  of  noisy  labels  on  classification  performance
can be greatly alleviated.
2) We elaborately design a teacher network in an
ensemble manner, named E-CA2-ResNet18, to solve the
unreliability and instability problem of teacher network
training resulted from the small-scale data samples.
3) We extensively validate our proposed CLA-KD
on three self-established TCM tongue datasets. The ex-
perimental results  on  three  datasets  show  that,  com-
pared with  the  existing  methods,  our  method  can  ob-
tain a superior performance with a lower network mod-
el complexity.
 II. Related Work
 1. Tongue color classification in TCM based
on deep learning
With the  rapid  development  of  deep  learning,  re-
searchers have tried to use its powerful feature extrac-
tion and  semantic  representative  capabilities  to  im-prove the performance of tongue color classification in
TCM [2], [3]. Hou et al. [4 ] constructed a tongue image
dataset and used a modified CaffeNet network to classi-
fy  the  tongue  color.  Chen et  al. [5 ]  proposed  a  new
method for extracting the color features of tongue im-
ages. They used the generalized Loyd algorithm (GLA)
algorithm to obtain the dominant color histogram. This
method effectively improved the accuracy of tongue col-
or classification. Lu et al. [6 ] proposed a deep color cor-
rection network to eliminate color distortion caused by
lighting conditions. Qu et al. [7 ] segmented the tongue
texture  regions  and  the  tongue  coating  regions,  and
used sparse coding to obtain the feature representation
vector of the tongue image for tongue color classifica-
tion.  In  addition,  considering  that  the  four  kinds  of
tongue color are in a sequential relationship, Gutiérrez
et  al. [8 ],  [9]  proposed  that  there  is  a  natural  order
between class labels. They confirmed that ordering in-
formation benefits classification models improving their
accuracy.
Generally, there are three kinds of data samples in
a  tongue  image  dataset:  clean  samples,  incorrect  label
samples,  and  inconsistent  label  samples.  As  shown  in
Fig.1, the tip of the tongue in Fig.1 (a) is reddish, but
the two sides of the tongue are lighter. For the TCM
experts, it is easily confused as the light red or red due
to the inherent characteristics of the tongue, leading to
different annotation results, i.e., inconsistent labels. In
 
