 Tongue Color Classification in TCM with Noisy Labels via Confident-Learning-Assisted Knowledge Distillation 141Fig.1(b)  and Fig.1 (c),  the  two  tongue  images  are
labeled as light red and red by TCM experts respect-
ively. But the color distribution is almost the same, as
shown in Fig.1(d), which results in incorrect labels.
Incorrect  labels  will  result  in  lower  accuracy  of
tongue color classification. Inconsistent labels often lead
to overfitting during the training process, and the early
model  optimization  is  hard  to  converge.  However,  the
existing tongue color classification methods generally do
not  take  the  noisy  labels  into  account.  Therefore,  the
classification performance is unsatisfactory and cannot
meet the requirements of practical applications.
 2. Image classification with noisy labels
Label  noise  is  a  great  challenge  for  the  training
process of DNNs. Therefore, it is necessary to consider
its existence and develop counter methods to efficiently
fade away its adverse effects on training DNNs. In the
recent  years,  learning  with  noisy  labels  is  extensively
studied in computer vision and machine learning com-
munities.  These  methods  are  categorized  into  two
groups: noise model based methods and noise model free
methods [10].
Noise  model  based  methods  aim  to  estimate  and
model the noise characteristics so that the obtained in-
formation can be used during training to avoid the ad-
verse effects of noisy labels. Northcutt et al. [11 ] pro-
posed  confident  learning  to  estimate  uncertainty  in
dataset labels. Xiao et al. [12 ] formulated noise into a
more  complex  function  for  modeling.  Veit et  al. [13]
used the method of label noise-cleansing to identify and
correct suspicious labels. In addition, data pruning [14]
can also weaken the influence of noisy labels on learn-
ing process. Luengo et al. [15 ] pruned the datasets ac-
cording to noise rate.
Differently,  noise  model  free  methods  [16]  aim  to
develop inherently noise robust strategies without expli-
cit modeling of the noise characteristics. The methods
mainly include robust loss function, meta-learning, reg-
ularization, ensemble learning [17], and so on [18], [19].
Ghosh et al. [20 ] proved that the mean absolute error
(MAE) is more tolerant to noise. Wang et al. [21 ] fur-
ther  proposed  an  improved  mean  absolute  error
(IMAE), which uses hyperparameters to scale the gradi-
ent to adjust the weighted variance. Garcia et al. [22]
proposed a meta-learning system for processing noisy la-
bels.  In  addition,  regularization  is  also  widely  used,
such as data augmentation [23], weight decay [24], dro-
pout [25], etc.
These methods mentioned above can alleviate the
impact  of  noise  on  the  classification  performance  to  a
certain extent, however, achieving a higher accuracy in
the presence of noisy labels is still a key challenge.
 3. Knowledge distillation
Our  approach  is  motivated  by  KD,  proposed  byHinton et al. The basic idea of distillation is to learn a
student model with a simpler network structure to re-
place  the  teacher  model  with  a  cumbersome  ensemble
model.  Specifically,  the  teacher  model  generates “soft
label” through training. And the student network tries
to make the output result consistent with the soft label
as  much  as  possible.  Similarly,  Cho et  al. [26 ] com-
bined a regularization strategy into distillation. Yang et
al. [27 ] added constraints to the teacher network. A key
insight from these studies is that soft distillation scores
are better than hard labels when guiding the learning of
student network.
Inspired by this, in this paper, a KD framework for
tongue color classification with noisy labels is proposed.
Firstly, we make the teacher model to perform CL for
data  pruning  and  label  correction  on  the  inconsistent
and  incorrect  labels.  And  then  we  use  the  corrected
data to train the teacher network. The output predic-
tion probability of the teacher network is used as soft
labels  to  guide  the  training  of  the  student  network,
which facilitates the student network to yield a compar-
able performance with the teacher network.
In this paper, we incorporate CL into the general
KD  framework  to  handle  the  noisy  labels.  It  can  not
only  mitigate  the  influence  of  noise  samples,  but  also
obtain  higher  classification  performance  with  a  light
weight CNN model.
